00:47:18.370 --> 00:47:19.828
JANCIS ROBINSON:
It's a lot cheaper

00:47:19.828 --> 00:47:21.520
than buying a
sportscar, much cheaper.

00:47:21.520 --> 00:47:22.710
And it's sociable.

00:47:22.710 --> 00:47:25.770
You can share it with your
friends more-- more friends

00:47:25.770 --> 00:47:27.594
than a sportscar.

00:47:27.594 --> 00:47:29.380
AUDIENCE: Do you
think climate change

00:47:29.380 --> 00:47:31.360
is going to have an
impact on which regions

00:47:31.360 --> 00:47:32.650
are interesting to--

00:47:32.650 --> 00:47:35.220
JANCIS ROBINSON: It's already
having quite a massive impact.

00:47:35.220 --> 00:47:40.940
And in fact, one of the
approx 3,000 free articles

00:47:40.940 --> 00:47:43.590
on my website I
published quite recently

00:47:43.590 --> 00:47:47.420
was specifically which regions
have been most affected,

00:47:47.420 --> 00:47:49.220
and what have been the
most obvious effects

00:47:49.220 --> 00:47:50.650
in the world of wine.

00:47:50.650 --> 00:47:55.680
One of the more obvious ones
is the poleward expansion

00:47:55.680 --> 00:47:58.500
of the wine regions
of the world.

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:00.510
There's not too much
further the south

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:03.150
the Southern Hemisphere
wine regions can go

00:48:03.150 --> 00:48:04.960
before topping into the ocean.

00:48:04.960 --> 00:48:08.230
But countries that now have
thriving wine industries

00:48:08.230 --> 00:48:12.430
include Denmark, Sweden,
Holland, Belgium,

00:48:12.430 --> 00:48:16.380
England, and there's
even a vineyard in Norway

00:48:16.380 --> 00:48:19.880
now, which has yet to
ripen a crop successfully,

00:48:19.880 --> 00:48:22.270
but it has been planted.

00:48:22.270 --> 00:48:24.260
So that's very obvious.

00:48:24.260 --> 00:48:26.240
Alcohol level's
going up, generally,

00:48:26.240 --> 00:48:29.365
because of more, hotter summers.

00:48:31.910 --> 00:48:35.050
And say somewhere like--
and then places running out

00:48:35.050 --> 00:48:36.930
of water, terrible
water shortages

00:48:36.930 --> 00:48:40.370
at times in California, and
particularly the inland areas

00:48:40.370 --> 00:48:41.300
of Australia.

00:48:41.300 --> 00:48:43.930
Quite a lot of grape
farmers have given up

00:48:43.930 --> 00:48:48.110
in those inland, irrigated areas
because it's just too expensive

00:48:48.110 --> 00:48:49.254
to buy the water rights.

00:48:49.254 --> 00:48:51.170
And there's also been a
problem with salinity,

00:48:51.170 --> 00:48:54.435
so to get good quality water
is too much of a challenge.

00:48:57.120 --> 00:48:59.590
And so in general, in
established wine regions,

00:48:59.590 --> 00:49:03.710
there's a move for people
to find cooler areas.

00:49:03.710 --> 00:49:07.320
You see that in
Burgundy, for instance.

00:49:07.320 --> 00:49:08.830
AUDIENCE: So in
Oxford, they're kind

00:49:08.830 --> 00:49:11.390
of notorious that the
colleges have wine cellars.

00:49:11.390 --> 00:49:16.510
Have you ever been around them,
and which one has the best wine

00:49:16.510 --> 00:49:17.010
collection?

00:49:17.010 --> 00:49:17.885
JANCIS ROBINSON: Yes.

00:49:17.885 --> 00:49:20.380
The best one is
All Soul's, which

00:49:20.380 --> 00:49:22.000
has no undergraduates at all.

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:24.420
And I have been around that
one, and it is amazing.

00:49:24.420 --> 00:49:26.950
I haven't been--
actually, I went round

00:49:26.950 --> 00:49:31.780
to write an article for Wine and
Spirits, which I left in 1980.

00:49:31.780 --> 00:49:36.050
So I'm not at all up to speed.

00:49:36.050 --> 00:49:38.420
But we made a television
program about the cellars

00:49:38.420 --> 00:49:41.640
at Lincoln, actually,
and it, like lots

00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:43.760
of the Oxbridge
sellers, has sold off

00:49:43.760 --> 00:49:45.140
a lot of vintage ports.

00:49:45.140 --> 00:49:47.610
They used to serve a
lot of vintage port,

00:49:47.610 --> 00:49:50.650
but don't anymore.

00:49:50.650 --> 00:49:56.100
But as I understand it, the job
of wine steward at the Oxbridge

00:49:56.100 --> 00:49:58.910
colleges is highly
sought after, and there's

00:49:58.910 --> 00:50:01.100
massive backstabbing to get it.

00:50:03.890 --> 00:50:06.060
There are lots and lots
of tastings in Oxbridge.

00:50:06.060 --> 00:50:08.340
The merchants, that's
one of the places

00:50:08.340 --> 00:50:10.230
where you can sell fine wine.

00:50:10.230 --> 00:50:13.750
So it is a good-- Oxbridge is
a good place to taste wine,

00:50:13.750 --> 00:50:17.790
and certainly that was where
I was introduced to fine wine

00:50:17.790 --> 00:50:21.820
and had my seminal bottle of red
Burgundy, which made me realize

00:50:21.820 --> 00:50:24.496
just how good wine could be.

00:50:28.869 --> 00:50:29.910
AUDIENCE: Quick question.

00:50:29.910 --> 00:50:32.750
From a marketing perspective,
are there any tricks

00:50:32.750 --> 00:50:35.670
that you have that
you'd use to make a wine

00:50:35.670 --> 00:50:37.660
seem like it tastes better?

00:50:37.660 --> 00:50:40.690
And I guess there's a
certain amount of ceremony

00:50:40.690 --> 00:50:45.992
that can influence how
people perceive taste.

00:50:45.992 --> 00:50:47.700
And I don't know
whether that's something

00:50:47.700 --> 00:50:49.960
that you address at
all, and the sort

00:50:49.960 --> 00:50:54.620
of things that you do to
help anticipation of a taste

00:50:54.620 --> 00:50:56.490
and anticipation is
something that actually

00:50:56.490 --> 00:50:58.900
does improve the taste.

00:50:58.900 --> 00:51:02.260
JANCIS ROBINSON: Well, most
of the time I'm judging wine,

00:51:02.260 --> 00:51:07.610
and so I have no interest in
making-- I want it as it is.

00:51:07.610 --> 00:51:09.290
I'm almost looking for faults.

00:51:09.290 --> 00:51:12.399
I'm analyzing it.

00:51:12.399 --> 00:51:14.690
There's a huge difference
between tasting and drinking,

00:51:14.690 --> 00:51:16.950
and tasting is what
I do during the day

00:51:16.950 --> 00:51:19.330
and I want to minimize
the effects of alcohol

00:51:19.330 --> 00:51:22.730
and I spit everything out,
and I'm super critical.

00:51:22.730 --> 00:51:25.719
But in the evening,
it's drink time,

00:51:25.719 --> 00:51:27.510
and that's a completely
different activity.

00:51:27.510 --> 00:51:29.920
And you're right, I want
to make the wine taste as

00:51:29.920 --> 00:51:31.530
good as possible,
particularly when

00:51:31.530 --> 00:51:34.590
I'm serving wine to friends.

00:51:34.590 --> 00:51:38.370
One very useful
trick is that if you

00:51:38.370 --> 00:51:40.690
have a young red
wine, which is still

00:51:40.690 --> 00:51:43.600
high in tannins, these
sort of chewy things

00:51:43.600 --> 00:51:45.720
that will preserve it
for quite a long time,

00:51:45.720 --> 00:51:49.770
but in youth they can be
quite astringent and obvious,

00:51:49.770 --> 00:51:53.810
the warmer you serve it the less
obvious the tannins will be.

00:51:53.810 --> 00:51:58.180
So that would be, say, a young
red Bordeaux, a young Cabernet.

00:51:58.180 --> 00:52:00.490
Serve it just a
little bit warmer

00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:05.230
than you would serve an old
wine, and it will taste softer.

00:52:05.230 --> 00:52:10.580
And if you actually have it with
a dish which is itself chewy,

00:52:10.580 --> 00:52:13.920
like a steak or a roast
or something like that,

00:52:13.920 --> 00:52:16.460
the wine will seem less chewy.

00:52:16.460 --> 00:52:20.430
And so those would be
good tips for flattering

00:52:20.430 --> 00:52:21.820
a young red wine.

00:52:25.170 --> 00:52:30.410
Don't-- wine is pretty-- unless,
it's a really sweet wine,

00:52:30.410 --> 00:52:34.110
wine is pretty
wrecked by sweet food.

00:52:34.110 --> 00:52:38.600
I mean, I look at people--
just the other night

00:52:38.600 --> 00:52:41.790
I was amazed to see people
ordering another glass of wine

00:52:41.790 --> 00:52:43.695
as the pudding
arrived, and I thought,

00:52:43.695 --> 00:52:46.690
that's not going to
taste of anything.

00:52:46.690 --> 00:52:52.540
So just be careful about serving
wine with anything very sweet.

00:52:52.540 --> 00:52:57.580
And I suppose things
that are very, very acid

00:52:57.580 --> 00:53:02.360
sometimes are tricky
partners for wine.

00:53:02.360 --> 00:53:05.810
And remember what I said about
temperature generally before.

00:53:05.810 --> 00:53:09.280
That can help.

00:53:09.280 --> 00:53:11.810
AUDIENCE: Just a question
around like, white wine and fish

00:53:11.810 --> 00:53:14.445
and red wine and
meats, and do you

00:53:14.445 --> 00:53:16.220
have a rule of when
do you actually

00:53:16.220 --> 00:53:18.400
have white wine with meat, or--

00:53:18.400 --> 00:53:20.100
JANCIS ROBINSON: No.

00:53:20.100 --> 00:53:29.320
If it's a very, very simple
poached sole, very delicate,

00:53:29.320 --> 00:53:35.080
say, then yes, to have a great
big, massive, chewy red wine

00:53:35.080 --> 00:53:36.320
wouldn't be a great match.

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:40.620
But a pinot noir, sort of light,
fruity red, absolutely fine.

00:53:40.620 --> 00:53:44.860
It's more about the color--
less about the color,

00:53:44.860 --> 00:53:48.850
more about the dimensions of
a wine, really-- great big.

00:53:48.850 --> 00:53:51.000
If you're having
a rich stew, then

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.890
have a kind of
big, powerful wine.

00:53:53.890 --> 00:53:57.552
And a delicate food, then have
a delicate wine, sort of thing.

00:53:57.552 --> 00:53:58.760
But the color doesn't matter.

00:53:58.760 --> 00:54:02.580
In Bordeaux, they
make largely red wine,

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:06.110
and they're always serving
fish with the red wine.

00:54:06.110 --> 00:54:09.260
But in general, a
fruity red is better

00:54:09.260 --> 00:54:11.200
than a chewy red with fish.

00:54:11.200 --> 00:54:15.921
So pinot noir would
be a good choice.

00:54:15.921 --> 00:54:17.712
AUDIENCE: I have a less
technical question.

00:54:17.712 --> 00:54:18.894
JANCIS ROBINSON: Yes.

00:54:18.894 --> 00:54:20.810
AUDIENCE: Does the queen
have a favorite wine?

00:54:20.810 --> 00:54:21.890
JANCIS ROBINSON: No.

00:54:21.890 --> 00:54:22.602
AUDIENCE: No.

00:54:22.602 --> 00:54:24.310
How often do you get
asked this question?

00:54:24.310 --> 00:54:25.910
All the time?

00:54:25.910 --> 00:54:28.190
JANCIS ROBINSON:
Especially abroad.

00:54:28.190 --> 00:54:31.149
No, I don't think
she's a big wine fan.

00:54:31.149 --> 00:54:31.690
AUDIENCE: Oh.

00:54:31.690 --> 00:54:33.523
JANCIS ROBINSON: But
she needs a lot of wine

00:54:33.523 --> 00:54:35.130
for all those
receptions and things.

00:54:35.130 --> 00:54:39.900
But because it all comes
out of the privy purse,

00:54:39.900 --> 00:54:43.480
we can't afford-- we don't
go for very expensive things

00:54:43.480 --> 00:54:45.910
for big receptions, because
we know the Daily Mail would

00:54:45.910 --> 00:54:46.770
get hold of it.

00:54:46.770 --> 00:54:48.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:49.450 --> 00:54:53.610
But it is fun to walk
into Buckingham Palace.

00:54:53.610 --> 00:54:56.540
I still get a sort
of childish thrill

00:54:56.540 --> 00:55:00.450
showing my driver's license
to the policeman on the gates

00:55:00.450 --> 00:55:03.530
and then crunching
over the gravel.

00:55:03.530 --> 00:55:05.030
SPEAKER 1: One last
question for me.

00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:08.940
So we touched on English wines.

00:55:08.940 --> 00:55:12.560
And there's a thriving
sparkling wine industry.

00:55:12.560 --> 00:55:14.020
Do you have any
favorite producers?

00:55:14.020 --> 00:55:16.460
JANCIS ROBINSON: Yes, I do,
and quite a few, actually.

00:55:16.460 --> 00:55:20.650
And again, I put them at
the end of an FT article,

00:55:20.650 --> 00:55:23.490
so they're at the end of a free
article on JancisRobinson.com.

00:55:23.490 --> 00:55:26.880
If you put English
wine in the search box,

00:55:26.880 --> 00:55:30.420
choose not tasting notes,
but everything else.

00:55:30.420 --> 00:55:34.150
I listed about 12.

00:55:34.150 --> 00:55:38.000
But one very good one,
Hambledon is very good,

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:41.900
came top of a blind tasting
I did with Champagnes.

00:55:41.900 --> 00:55:43.812
I mean, beating the Champagnes.

00:55:43.812 --> 00:55:45.020
SPEAKER 1: Thank you so much.

00:55:45.020 --> 00:55:46.103
JANCIS ROBINSON: Pleasure.

00:55:46.103 --> 00:55:48.370
